<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-compound-interest" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Compound Interest</title>
    <!--  -->
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <p>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.0 Measurement and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.4 Commercial Arithmetic
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title> 
                    <p>
                            <ul>
                              <li>Derive compound interest formula using the step by step method</li>
                              <li>Determine compound interest using the compound interest formula</li>
                            </ul>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p>
                        11
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p>
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    15 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To compare simple interest and compound interest and identify the pattern formed by compound interest.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>
                    Group learners into squads of <m>3</m> or <m>4</m>. Ensure they realize that for Option A, the interest stays constant at Ksh <m>1,000</m> every single year because the principal remains fixed. For Option B, guide them to notice that the new principal for Year <m>2</m> is Ksh <m>11,000</m>, which yields Ksh <m>1,100</m> in interest. Encourage groups to look at the expanding values and discuss why Option B runs away from Option A over long timelines.
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>
     <activity>
        <statement>
            <p>
                <term>Work in Groups</term>
            </p>
            <p>
                A youth group in Kisumu County want to invest Ksh <m>10,000</m> for <m>3</m> years. The bank offers two investment options.
            </p>
            <p>
                Option A : The interest is calculated on the original amount for the period of investment.
            </p>
            <p>
                Option B : The interest is calculated on the original amount and the interest accumulated at the end of each year for the period of investment.
            </p>
            <p>
                If the interest rate is given to be <m>10 \%</m> p.a for both options.
            </p>
            <p>
                <term>In Groups</term> 
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Calculate using option A,
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <ol marker="(i)">
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        Interest earned each year for the three years?
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        Total interest earned each year for the three years?
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        Total amount at the end of three years?
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Does the interest earned change each year? What stays constant in the system? Why?
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Calculate using option B,
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <ol marker="(i)">
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        Interest earned each year for the three years?
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        Total interest earned each year for the three years?
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        Total amount at the end of three years?
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Does the interest earned change each year? What is changing in the system? Why?
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
            <p>
                <term>Use your results</term> to write the amounts obtained in Option B using powers.
            </p>
            <p>
                Predict the amount after:
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>4</m> years?
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>5</m> years?
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>T</m> years?
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
            
        </statement>
     </activity>

    
    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Structured Instruction</title>
        <p>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Suggested Time</title>
                    <p>
                        10 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Objective</title>
                    <p>
                        To help learners derive the compound interest formula from repeated yearly growth.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
        <paragraphs>
            <title>Key Takeaways &amp; Teacher Connection</title>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Discussion:</alert> Discuss the results obtained by learners in the two investment options. Point out that in Option A the same amount of interest is earned each year because interest is calculated on the original principal.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Developing the Formula:</alert> In Option B, the amount at the end of each year becomes the starting amount for the next year. Guide learners to write the amounts after Year <m>1</m> and Year <m>2</m> and identify the pattern.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Observing the Pattern:</alert> Learners should observe that the same factor <m>\left(1+\frac{R}{100}\right)</m> is multiplied each year, giving <m>P\left(1+\frac{R}{100}\right)^T</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </paragraphs>
    </axiom>

    
    <insight>
        <p>
            From the activity, learners observe that:
        </p>
        <p>
            <ol marker="(a)">
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Amount after year <m>1</m>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <md>
                            <mrow>110,000 = \amp \; 100,000 + 10,000 </mrow>
                            <mrow> = \amp \; 100,000\left(1 + 0.1\right) </mrow>
                            <mrow> = \amp \; 100,000 \left( 1 + \frac{10}{100}\right) </mrow>
                        </md>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Amount after <m>2</m> years
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        At the beginning of the second year, the accumulated amount is Ksh <m>110,000</m>.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <md>
                            <mrow>\text{Interest} \; =\amp \; \frac{R}{100} \times P </mrow>
                            <mrow> I = \amp \; \frac{10}{100}\times 100,000\left(1 + \frac{10}{100}\right) </mrow>
                            <mrow> A = \amp \; P + I </mrow>
                            <mrow> = \amp \; 100,000 \left(1 + \frac{10}{100}\right) +  \frac{10}{100}\times 100,000\left(1 + \frac{10}{100}\right) </mrow>
                            <mrow> = \amp \; 100,000 \left(1 + \frac{10}{100}\right) \left(1 + \frac{10}{100}\right) </mrow>
                            <mrow> 121,000 = \amp \;100,000 \left(1 + \frac{10}{100}\right)^2  </mrow>
                        </md>
                        
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        What is the amount after <m>3,4,5</m> years?
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
        <p>
            The general formula for Compound interest is therefore;
        </p>
        <p>
            <md>
                <mrow> A = \amp \; P \left( 1 + \frac{R}{100}\right) ^ T </mrow>
                <mrow> CI = \amp \; A - P </mrow>
            </md>
            where
            <ol marker="(i)">
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>A</m> is the amount,
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>P</m> is the principal,
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>R</m> is the rate,
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>T</m> is the time in years,
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
            
        </p>
    </insight>

    <!-- Add further instruction (not in a block) to develop ideas as needed -->

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/example-intro.ptx" />

    <!-- Add at least 3 examples -->

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
              Onyimbo invest Ksh <m>3,000</m> in an investment account paying <m>3 \%</m> interest compounded quarterly, how much will the account be worth in <m>10</m> years?  
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Given:
            </p>    
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>p = \amp \; 3000 </mrow>
                    <mrow>r = \amp \; 0.03 </mrow>
                    <mrow>n = \amp \; 4 </mrow>
                    <mrow>t = \amp \; 10 </mrow>
                </md>
                
            </p>
            <p>
            <md>
                <mrow>A(t) = &amp; P\left(1+\frac{r}{n}\right)^{nt}</mrow>
                <mrow>A(10) = &amp; 3000\left(1+\frac{0.03}{4}\right)^{4⋅10} </mrow>
                <mrow>≈\text{Ksh} \;4045.05 &amp; \text{ Round to two decimal places }.</mrow>
            </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                The account will be worth about Ksh <m>4,045.05</m> in 10 years.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Lily wishes to save money for her granddaughter's university education and wants the account to grow to Ksh <m>400,000</m> over <m>18</m> years. The account earns <m>6</m> % compounded semi-annually. To the nearest Ksh, how much will Lily need to invest in the account now?
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                The nominal interest rate is <m>6 \%</m>, so <m>r=0.06.</m> Interest is compounded twice a year, so <m>n=2.</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                We want to find the initial investment, <m>P,</m> needed so that the value of the account will be worth Ksh <m>400,000</m> in <m>18</m> years. Substitute the given values into the compound interest formula, and solve for <m>P.</m>
            </p>
            <p>
            <md>
                <mrow>A(t) = &amp; P\left(1+\frac{r}{n}\right)^{nt} </mrow>
                <mrow>400,000 = &amp; P\left(1+\frac{0.06}{2}\right)^{2(18)} </mrow>
                <mrow>400,000 = &amp; P(1.03)^{36}</mrow>
                <mrow>\frac{400,000}{(1.03)^{36}} = &amp; P </mrow>
                <mrow>P = &amp; \text{Ksh}\;138,010 </mrow>
            </md>
            </p>
            <p>Lily will need to invest Ksh <m>138,010</m> to have Ksh <m>400,000</m> in <m>18</m> years.</p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                An investor has <m>50,000</m> Shillings to save for <m>2</m> years. They are offered a nominal interest rate of <m>12 \%</m> per annum. Calculate and compare the total interest earned if the interest is
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Compounded Annually
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Compounded Semi-Annually
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow> P = \amp  \; \text{Ksh} \; 50,000</mrow>
                    <mrow> R = \amp 12 \;\% </mrow>
                    <mrow> T = \amp 2 \; \text{years} </mrow>
                </md>
                
            </p>
            <p>
                Applying the compound interest formula <m>A = P \left(1 + \frac{R}{100}\right) ^T</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                           <md>
                                <mrow> A = \amp 50,000 \left(1 + \frac{12}{100}\right)^2 </mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp 50,000(1.12)^2 </mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp 62,720 \;\text{shillings} </mrow>
                           </md>
                            
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Interest is therefore equals <m>62,720 - 50,000 = 12,720 \;\text{shillings}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            We adjust the rates to <m>R = \frac{12\;\%}{2} = 6 \;\% </m> and time to <m>4 \;\text{years}</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Applying the compound interest formula gives
                            <md>
                                <mrow> A = \amp \;50,000 \left(1 + \frac{6}{100}\right)^4</mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp \;50,000(1.006)^4 </mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp \; 63,123.85 \;\text{shillings} </mrow>
                            </md>
                            
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            The interest compounded semi annually is <m>63,123.85 - 50,000 = 13,123.85 \;\text{shillings}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example>
        <title>Comparing Compounding Frequency vs. Nominal Rate</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                An entrepreneur wants to invest <m>100,000</m> Shillings for <m>1</m> year. They must choose between two competing bank offers:
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                           <alert>Bank A:</alert> Offers <m>12\%</m> per annum compounded Quarterly.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Bank B:</alert> Offers <m>12.5\%</m> per annum compounded Annually.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
            <p>
                Which bank option should the entrepreneur choose?
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            For Bank A, the annual nominal rate is <m>12\%</m> compounded quarterly over <m>4</m> periods. We adjust our calculations where:
                            <m>R = \frac{12\%}{4} = 3\% = 0.03 \text{ per period}</m>
                            <m>n = 4 \text{ periods}</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Apply the compound accumulation formula:
                            <md>
                                <mrow> A = \amp \; 100,000(1 + 0.03)^4 </mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp \; 100,000(1.1255088) </mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp \; 112,550.88 \text{ Shillings} </mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Total interest earned from Bank A <m> = 12,550.88 \text{ Shillings}</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            For Bank B, the rate is <m>12.5\%</m> compounded annually over a single period.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Apply the annual interest calculation:
                            <md>
                                <mrow> A = \amp \; 100,000(1 + 0.125)^1 </mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp \; 112,500 \text{ Shillings} </mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Total interest earned from Bank B <m> = 12,500 \text{ Shillings}</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
            <p>
                <alert>Decision Conclusion:</alert> The entrepreneur should choose <alert>Bank A</alert>. Even though Bank B offers a higher nominal starting rate (<m>12.5\%</m> vs <m>12\%</m>), Bank A gives a slightly higher return because interest is added four times during the year.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
